        <p>We ran 10 platforms across three fresh test sites over 90 days. Here is the ranking by what actually ships without intervention, what cost per article looks like, and where the autopilot story starts to leak.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — Pick by what you want on autopilot</div>
          <p><strong>Full content + local pipeline:</strong> theStacc ($99/mo, 30 articles). <strong>Technical + on-page agent:</strong> Search Atlas OTTO ($149/mo). <strong>Cheapest entry-tier:</strong> SEO Bot ($19/mo) or Emplibot ($49/mo). <strong>Daily content cadence:</strong> RankYak ($79/mo). <strong>Multilingual:</strong> Arvow.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Want true autopilot, not "AI assist"?</h4>
            <p>theStacc handles research, briefs, writing, optimisation, and publishing to WordPress / Webflow / Ghost. <strong>30 SEO articles a month for $99</strong> — pair with the Local SEO module for $49/mo more.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">See a live demo <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">No card · 15-min walkthrough</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="what-is">What makes a tool real SEO autopilot</h2>
        <p>Most "autopilot" tools score 2–3 out of the 5 things they should automate. The full bar in 2026:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keyword research</strong> — generated from a seed, not asked of you.</li>
          <li><strong>Briefs and outlines</strong> — SERP-driven, not template-based.</li>
          <li><strong>Drafting</strong> — full-length, on-brand, with internal links pre-wired.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimisation</strong> — SERP scoring, schema, meta, alt text auto-applied.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing</strong> — direct to WordPress / Webflow / Ghost on a schedule.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">⚠️ The "autopilot" leak</div>
          <p>Most tools advertise autopilot but stop at the draft. <strong>You still review, edit, paste, set the featured image, and click publish on every article.</strong> If a tool requires a human to click "approve" before anything ships, it is an assist, not an autopilot. Read the docs for the word "publish" before you sign up.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-we-tested">How we tested 10 autopilot platforms</h2>
        <p>Same seed keyword list, same 30-article target, same 90-day window.</p>

