        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the best SEO autopilot software in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>theStacc is our top pick — $99/mo for 30 SEO articles researched, written, optimised, and published to your CMS, plus the option to bundle GBP and social. For technical-led autopilot, Search Atlas OTTO. For the cheapest entry point, SEO Bot. For multilingual, Arvow. The best fit depends on whether content, technical, or local is your bottleneck.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What does SEO autopilot software actually do?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>True autopilot platforms chain the full content pipeline — keyword research, brief, draft, on-page optimisation, internal linking, and publishing to WordPress / Webflow / Ghost — without a human in the loop. The best add technical on-page fixes (schema, meta, alt text) and local SEO automation on top.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is SEO autopilot safe for Google rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, when the platform produces well-researched, original, and useful content. Google's guidance is that content quality matters, not how it was produced. The platforms that get sites in trouble are spinners and thin-content generators — not modern autopilot tools that combine LLM drafting with research, brief, and on-page best practice.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How is autopilot different from AI writing tools like Jasper?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>AI writers help you draft inside an editor. Autopilot tools take a seed list, do the keyword research, write the article, optimise it, and push it to your CMS — with no human in the loop. Jasper assists; theStacc and OTTO operate. You can use AI writers without ever shipping; you can't really use an autopilot tool without shipping articles.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How much does SEO autopilot cost?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Entry-tier autopilot tools like SEO Bot and Emplibot start around $19–$49/mo for low-volume sites. Mid-market platforms like RankYak and Outrank sit at $79–$99/mo. theStacc is $99/mo for 30 articles. Enterprise and agency tiers like Search Atlas and Adaptify run $149–$499/mo with multi-site support.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Will I still need a writer if I use SEO autopilot?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Most small and mid-market sites won't. A good autopilot platform produces publish-ready articles every week — the founder usually keeps a thought-leadership post or two per month as the human voice. Writers stay useful for podcasts, opinion pieces, and high-stakes top-of-funnel content, but the recurring SEO grind is fully handled.</p></div></div>
